// Man page for email
manEmail="EMAIL(1)                         X Shell Manual                         EMAIL(1)

<b>NAME</b>
    email - Email client and mail management
<b>SYNOPSIS</b>
    <b>email</b> <b>-c</b> ([EMAIL] [PASSWORD])
    <b>[pipe] | email -c</b>
    <b>[pipe] | email -l</b>
    <b>email</b> <b>-v</b>
    <b>email</b> <b>-o</b> ID
    <b>email</b> <b>-l</b> [USER] ([PASSWORD])
    <b>email</b> <b>-s</b>
    <b>email</b> <b>-n</b>
    <b>email</b> <b>-b</b> RECIPIENT SUBJECT MESSAGE [COUNT]
    <b>email</b> <b>-r</b> ID
    <b>email</b> <b>-x</b>
    <b>email</b> <b>-cc</b> [-a]
    <b>email</b> <b>-m</b> ACCOUNT PASSWORD REFRESH
<b>DESCRIPTION</b>
    Command-line email client for reading, composing, and managing messages.
    Supports account login, inbox monitoring, email bombing, and automated
    mail operations. Essential for social engineering and phishing campaigns (When Kuro get is head out of his arse).

    <color=#e4ff34>*** Use [A] in the client to switch accounts within a session ***</color>
<b>OPTIONS</b>
    <b>-c</b> ([EMAIL] [PASSWORD])
    Open email client interface
    Launch GUI for email management
    Optionally pass email and password to open a specific account directly
    Also accepts piped input: <b>echo ""user@mail.com pass"" | email -c</b>

    <b>-v</b>
    View inbox messages
    List all emails in current account

    <b>-o</b> ID
    Open specific email by ID
    Display full email content

    <b>-l</b> [USER] ([PASSWORD])
    Login to email account
    Prompts for password if not provided

    <b>-s</b>
    Setup new email account configuration
    Register account with framework

    <b>-n</b>
    Compose new email message
    Interactive message composition

    <b>-b</b> RECIPIENT SUBJECT MESSAGE [COUNT]
    Email bomb attack
    Send multiple messages, COUNT defaults to 10

    <b>-r</b> ID
    Remove email by ID
    Delete specific message from inbox

    <b>-x</b>
    Clear all emails from inbox
    Purge entire mailbox

    <b>-cc</b> [-a]
    Clear saved credentials file
    Resets the stored email account from the framework
    Use <b>-a</b> to immediately re-prompt for new credentials after clearing

    <b>-m</b> ACCOUNT PASSWORD REFRESH
    Monitor account with auto-refresh
    All three arguments required
<b>EXAMPLE:</b>
    <color=#e4ff34># Account Management</color>
    <b>email -s</b>
    Setup new account

    <b>email -l user@mail.com</b>
    Login with password prompt

    <b>email -l admin@corp.com secretpass</b>
    Direct login with password

    <color=#e4ff34># Reading Email</color>
    <b>email -c</b>
    Open email client GUI

    <b>email -c victim@corp.com password123</b>
    Open client logged in as another account

    <b>echo ""victim@corp.com password123"" | email -c</b>
    Open client with piped credentials

    <b>cat creds.txt | email -l</b>
    Login with piped credentials

    <b>email -v</b>
    View all messages in inbox

    <b>email -o 5</b>
    Open email ID 5

    <color=#e4ff34># Sending Email</color>
    <b>email -n</b>
    Compose new message

    <color=#e4ff34># Email Bombing</color>
    <b>email -b target@victim.com Spam Test 100</b>
    Send 100 test messages

    <b>email -b admin@corp.com Alert Security 500</b>
    Flood with 500 messages

    <color=#e4ff34># Cleanup</color>
    <b>email -r 12</b>
    Delete email ID 12

    <b>email -x</b>
    Clear entire inbox

    <color=#e4ff34># Credentials</color>
    <b>email -cc</b>
    Remove saved credentials

    <b>email -cc -a</b>
    Remove saved credentials and re-setup

    <color=#e4ff34># Monitoring</color>
    <b>email -m user@mail.com pass123 30</b>
    Monitor with 30-second refresh
<b>SEE ALSO</b>
    <b>open</b>, <b>notes</b>"